{"title_page": "Mark Alarie", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NBA biography\n| name         = Mark Alarie\n| image        = \n| width        =\n| caption      =\n| position     = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft    = 6\n| height_in    = 7\n| weight_lb    = 217\n| number       = 32, 31\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1963|12|11}}\n| birth_place  = [[Phoenix, Arizona]]\n| nationality  = American\n| high_school  = [[Brophy College Preparatory|Brophy Prep]] (Phoenix, Arizona)\n| college      = [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]] (1982\u20131986)\n| draft_year   = 1986\n| draft_round  = 1\n| draft_pick   = 18\n| draft_team   = [[Denver Nuggets]]\n| career_start = 1986\n| career_end   = 1991\n| years1          = {{nbay|1986|full=y}}\n| team1           = [[Denver Nuggets]]\n| years2          = {{nbay|1987|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1990|end}}\n| team2           = [[Washington Bullets]]\n| highlights =\n* Third-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] \u2013 [[United Press International|UPI]] ([[1986 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1986]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-[[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] (1984, 1986)\n* Fourth-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (1982)\n| stats_league    = NBA\n| stat1label      = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value      = 2,432 (7.5 ppg)\n| stat2label      = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value      = 1,120 (3.4 rpg)\n| bbr             = alarima01\n}}\n'''Mark Steven Alarie''' (born December 11, 1963) is a retired American professional [[basketball]] player who played in the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]. He was listed at 6'7\" and 217&nbsp;lb.\n\nAlarie attended [[Brophy College Preparatory]], where he was the Arizona Player of the Year for 1982 after averaging 29.9 points and 17.3 rebounds per game. Alarie was named the state's No. 4 player on The Arizona Republic's All-Century team in 2000 and was inducted into the azcentral High School Sports Hall of Fame in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=High School Hall of Fame: Mark Alarie|date=2008|work=azcentral.com|url=http://www.archive.azcentral.com/sports/preps/articles/high-school-hall-of-fame-2008-inductees.html|accessdate=January 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter high school, he went to [[Duke University]], where he was a two-time All-Atlantic Coast Conference first team selection and a third team All-American as a senior in 1986, when Duke played in the [[NCAA]] championship game. Alarie was drafted in the first round, as the 18th pick of the [[1986 NBA draft]], by the [[Denver Nuggets]] (playing there one season).\n\nAlarie's fourth season was his best, averaging 10.5 points and 4.6 rebounds per game for the [[Washington Bullets]] (1987\u20131991, retired aged 27 due to recurring knee injuries).\n\nAlarie's daughter Isabella, known as Bella, attended [[Princeton University|Princeton]] and played on the [[Princeton Tigers women's basketball|basketball team]] from 2016 to 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/recruiting-insider/wp/2015/02/06/national-cathedrals-isabella-alarie-grows-out-of-fathers-shadow/ |title=National Cathedral's Isabella Alarie grows out of father\u2019s shadow |last=Giannotto |first=Mark |date=February 6, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=July 21, 2017}}</ref> She received numerous Ivy League honors during her first year<ref>[http://www.goprincetontigers.com/news/2017/3/31/womens-basketball-season-recap-princeton-reaches-eighth-straight-postseason-tournament.aspx Princeton reaches eighth straight postseason tournament]</ref> and went on to be named Ivy League Player of the Year in her final three seasons.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://ivyleague.com/news/2020/3/11/womens-basketball-announces-major-awards-and-all-ivy-after-another-accomplished-season.aspx |title=Women's Basketball Announces Major Awards and All-Ivy After Another Accomplished Season |publisher=Ivy League |date=March 11, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Bella was projected by Mechelle Voepel of [[ESPN]] as a mid-first-round pick in the [[2020 WNBA draft]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/wnba/story/_/id/29008593/wnba-mock-draft-2020-oregon-sabrina-ionescu-satou-sabally-projected-go-1-2 |title=WNBA mock draft 2020 \u2013 Oregon's Sabrina Ionescu, Satou Sabally projected to go 1-2 |first=Mechelle |last=Voepel |website=ESPN.com |date=April 8, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{basketball-reference|id=a/alarima01|name=Mark Alarie}}\n*[http://www.crosshill.com/board.html Mark Alarie] business bio\n\n{{1986 NBA Draft}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Alarie, Mark}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:All-American college men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:American men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Basketball players at the 1986 NCAA Men's Division I Final Four]]\n[[Category:Basketball players from Arizona]]\n[[Category:Denver Nuggets draft picks]]\n[[Category:Denver Nuggets players]]\n[[Category:Duke Blue Devils men's basketball players]]\n[[Category:Navy Midshipmen men's basketball coaches]]\n[[Category:Parade High School All-Americans (boys' basketball)]]\n[[Category:Small forwards]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Phoenix, Arizona]]\n[[Category:Washington Bullets players]]\n\n\n{{1960s-US-basketball-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NBA biography\n| name         = Mark Alarie\n| image        = \n| width        =\n| caption      =\n| position     = [[Power forward (basketball)|Power forward]]\n| height_ft    = 6\n| height_in    = 7\n| weight_lb    = 217\n| number       = 32, 31\n| birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1963|12|11}}\n| birth_place  = [[Phoenix, Arizona]]\n| nationality  = American\n| high_school  = [[Brophy College Preparatory|Brophy Prep]] (Phoenix, Arizona)\n| college      = [[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]] (1982\u20131986)\n| draft_year   = 1986\n| draft_round  = 1\n| draft_pick   = 18\n| draft_team   = [[Denver Nuggets]]\n| career_start = 1986\n| career_end   = 1991\n| years1          = {{nbay|1986|full=y}}\n| team1           = [[Denver Nuggets]]\n| years2          = {{nbay|1987|start}}\u2013{{nbay|1990|end}}\n| team2           = [[Washington Bullets]]\n| highlights =\n* Third-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] \u2013 [[United Press International|UPI]] ([[1986 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1986]])\n* 2\u00d7 First-team All-[[Atlantic Coast Conference|ACC]] (1984, 1986)\n* Fourth-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (1982)\n| stats_league    = NBA\n| stat1label      = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value      = 2,432 (7.5 ppg)\n| stat2label      = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value      = 1,120 (3.4 rpg)\n| bbr             = alarima01\n}}\n'''Mark Steven Alarie''' (born December 11, 1963) is a retired American professional [[basketball]] player who played in the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]]. He was listed at 6'7\" and 217&nbsp;lb.\n\nAlarie attended [[Brophy College Preparatory]], where he was the Arizona Player of the Year for 1982 after averaging 29.9 points and 17.3 rebounds per game. Alarie was named the state's No. 4 player on The Arizona Republic's All-Century team in 2000 and was inducted into the azcentral High School Sports Hall of Fame in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=High School Hall of Fame: Mark Alarie|date=2008|work=azcentral.com|url=http://www.archive.azcentral.com/sports/preps/articles/high-school-hall-of-fame-2008-inductees.html|accessdate=January 8, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAfter high school, he went to [[Duke University]], where he was a two-time All-Atlantic Coast Conference first team selection and a third team All-American as a senior in 1986, when Duke played in the [[NCAA]] championship game. Alarie was drafted in the first round, as the 18th pick of the [[1986 NBA draft]], by the [[Denver Nuggets]] (playing there one season).\n\nAlarie's fourth season was his best, averaging 10.5 points and 4.6 rebounds per game for the [[Washington Bullets]] (1987\u20131991, retired aged 27 due to recurring knee injuries).\n\nAlarie's daughter Isabella, publicly known as Bella, attended [[Princeton University|Princeton]] and played on the [[Princeton Tigers women's basketball|basketball team]] from 2016 to 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/recruiting-insider/wp/2015/02/06/national-cathedrals-isabella-alarie-grows-out-of-fathers-shadow/ |title=National Cathedral's Isabella Alarie grows out of father\u2019s shadow |last=Giannotto |first=Mark |date=February 6, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=July 21, 2017}}</ref> She received numerous Ivy League honors during her first year<ref>[http://www.goprincetontigers.com/news/2017/3/31/womens-basketball-season-recap-princeton-reaches-eighth-straight-postseason-tournament.aspx Princeton reaches eighth straight postseason tournament]</ref> and went on to be named Ivy League Player of the Year in her final three seasons.<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://ivyleague.com/news/2020/3/11/womens-basketball-announces-major-awards-and-all-ivy-after-another-accomplished-season.aspx |title=Women's Basketball Announces Major Awards and All-Ivy After Another Accomplished Season |publisher=Ivy League |date=March 11, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Bella was projected by Mechelle Voepel of [[ESPN]] as a mid-first-round pick in the [[2020 WNBA draft]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.espn.com/wnba/story/_/id/29008593/wnba-mock-draft-2020-oregon-sabrina-ionescu-satou-sabally-projected-go-1-2 |title=WNBA mock draft 2020 \u2013 Oregon's Sabrina Ionescu, Satou Sabally projected to go 1-2 |first=Mechelle |last=Voepel |website=ESPN.com |date=April 8, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{baske